KANWER SINGH: Yes.

00:09:32.755 --> 00:09:32.850
TY WARD: Yeah?

00:09:32.850 --> 00:09:33.660
KANWER SINGH: Very.

00:09:33.660 --> 00:09:35.035
TY WARD: So this
is not something

00:09:35.035 --> 00:09:37.000
that just came with your rise.

00:09:37.000 --> 00:09:39.595
It's like, you always had
that spirit of, I got this.

00:09:39.595 --> 00:09:41.470
KANWER SINGH: I've been
stubborn and defiant.

00:09:41.470 --> 00:09:45.460
And yeah, just recently,
I connected with a cousin.

00:09:45.460 --> 00:09:47.530
He lives in New Zealand.

00:09:47.530 --> 00:09:50.530
And our schedules
matched up in Germany,

00:09:50.530 --> 00:09:53.950
and I met him for the
first time since like '93.

00:09:53.950 --> 00:09:56.830
And he said to me, my
first memory of you

00:09:56.830 --> 00:09:58.300
was you were like
five years old,

00:09:58.300 --> 00:10:00.670
and you just kept
looking at me saying, no.

00:10:00.670 --> 00:10:02.757
And I wasn't even asking
you to do anything.

00:10:02.757 --> 00:10:04.340
You just kept looking
at me defiantly,

00:10:04.340 --> 00:10:06.923
like if you do ask me to do
something, the answer is no.

00:10:06.923 --> 00:10:09.340
And I kind of realized that
that kind of clicked something

00:10:09.340 --> 00:10:13.810
in the patterns in my life,
where I definitely am not

00:10:13.810 --> 00:10:15.850
a fan of being told what to do.

00:10:15.850 --> 00:10:19.390
I definitely enjoy the idea
of trying to mold things

00:10:19.390 --> 00:10:21.730
my way, versus trying to fit in.

00:10:21.730 --> 00:10:23.800
And there were a
lot of challenging

00:10:23.800 --> 00:10:26.630
years where I definitely didn't
fit in, and it almost broke me.

00:10:26.630 --> 00:10:29.030
And I wanted to just give
up and kind of blend in

00:10:29.030 --> 00:10:30.900
with everybody else.

00:10:30.900 --> 00:10:35.780
But then eventually, you
realize that, as Dr. Seuss says,

00:10:35.780 --> 00:10:37.977
why try to fit in when you
were born to stand out?

00:10:37.977 --> 00:10:39.560
TY WARD: It's funny
that you say that.

00:10:39.560 --> 00:10:42.637
So we have a building
here on campus, Bin 7--

00:10:42.637 --> 00:10:43.720
oh, nope, I made that up--

00:10:43.720 --> 00:10:46.035
Bin 4 that literally has that--

00:10:46.035 --> 00:10:47.160
KANWER SINGH: Oh, for real?

00:10:47.160 --> 00:10:49.550
TY WARD: Printed on the wall,
coincidentally on the way

00:10:49.550 --> 00:10:50.588
to the bathroom.

00:10:50.588 --> 00:10:51.380
KANWER SINGH: Nice.

00:10:51.380 --> 00:10:53.838
TY WARD: I'm not really sure
what the idea behind that was,

00:10:53.838 --> 00:10:55.610
but I just noticed
it for the first time

00:10:55.610 --> 00:10:56.330
yesterday, because
I love that quote.

00:10:56.330 --> 00:10:57.930
KANWER SINGH: That's dope.

00:10:57.930 --> 00:11:01.520
TY WARD: OK, so you
mentioned that you grew up

00:11:01.520 --> 00:11:04.340
with Sikh religious background.

00:11:04.340 --> 00:11:10.460
My curiosity there is so we
have a audacious Humble, young

00:11:10.460 --> 00:11:13.040
Humble, Sikh
religious background.

00:11:13.040 --> 00:11:16.490
How did the two of those
influences meet together?

00:11:16.490 --> 00:11:19.220
And how have they
shaped you, like how

00:11:19.220 --> 00:11:23.030
you lived your life and
ultimately, written this book?

00:11:23.030 --> 00:11:26.030
KANWER SINGH: I mean,
definitely, Sikhi

00:11:26.030 --> 00:11:27.530
can be viewed as a religion.

00:11:27.530 --> 00:11:30.170
I think more importantly,
it's more of a philosophy,

00:11:30.170 --> 00:11:32.030
and it more kind of
falls under the umbrella

00:11:32.030 --> 00:11:34.860
of eastern philosophy, when
you think about Buddhism,

00:11:34.860 --> 00:11:37.940
Hinduism-- just the
idea of cyclical life.

00:11:37.940 --> 00:11:40.280
Out here, a lot of
the philosophies,

00:11:40.280 --> 00:11:42.112
whether it's Christianity,
Judaism, Islam,

00:11:42.112 --> 00:11:44.570
are straight lines, through
the beginning, middle, and end.

00:11:44.570 --> 00:11:46.220
Do all these things,
and then there's

00:11:46.220 --> 00:11:49.440
something, a reward or a
consequence at the end of it.

00:11:49.440 --> 00:11:53.030
Whereas on the eastern side,
everything's in a cycle.

00:11:53.030 --> 00:11:55.610
Birth and death, the seasons,
everything go that way.

00:11:55.610 --> 00:11:57.500
So I think under those
two umbrellas, they

00:11:57.500 --> 00:11:59.630
only kind of look at
the world being shaped

00:11:59.630 --> 00:12:01.970
by those main philosophies.

00:12:01.970 --> 00:12:05.720
My parents force fed Sikhi
as a dogmatic religion

00:12:05.720 --> 00:12:08.450
to me as a kid the
same way parents force

00:12:08.450 --> 00:12:09.950
their kids to play the piano.

00:12:09.950 --> 00:12:13.160
And you hate every moment
of it, but then you grow up,

00:12:13.160 --> 00:12:16.640
and you're like, oh, now
I have a really full tool

00:12:16.640 --> 00:12:18.890
belt of things that are
really going to benefit me.

00:12:18.890 --> 00:12:22.813
And I mean, the idea that
turmeric is so popular now

00:12:22.813 --> 00:12:23.730
and everybody eats it.

00:12:23.730 --> 00:12:26.000
And that was the stuff the
kids would make fun of me

00:12:26.000 --> 00:12:28.220
for having stains on my clothes.

00:12:28.220 --> 00:12:29.940
And they'd call it
curry back then.

00:12:29.940 --> 00:12:33.390
And it's kind of like seeing
how things have changed so much.

00:12:33.390 --> 00:12:35.930
So I think what it
ended up being was,

00:12:35.930 --> 00:12:38.660
my mom kind of sold the idea to
me, telling me these stories.

00:12:38.660 --> 00:12:43.130
Because there's a lot of civil
disobedience in Sikh heritage.

00:12:43.130 --> 00:12:46.070
Punjabi Sikh specifically
in India right now only

00:12:46.070 --> 00:12:48.480
represent 2% of the population.

00:12:48.480 --> 00:12:50.227
So I'm a minority there.

00:12:50.227 --> 00:12:51.060
I'm a minority here.

00:12:51.060 --> 00:12:52.680
I'm a minority everywhere I go.

00:12:52.680 --> 00:12:56.030
So ideas of safe spaces
don't exist for me,

00:12:56.030 --> 00:12:57.140
don't exist for my people.

00:12:57.140 --> 00:12:59.150
We've never had them.

00:12:59.150 --> 00:13:00.740
If we do have them,
we'll probably

00:13:00.740 --> 00:13:02.630
feel very uncomfortable
because that's not

00:13:02.630 --> 00:13:04.340
something we're used to.

00:13:04.340 --> 00:13:06.920
Kind of having a history
of thriving in chaos,

00:13:06.920 --> 00:13:11.030
having a history of not being
planted on one piece of land

00:13:11.030 --> 00:13:15.290
has definitely encouraged me to
continue my nomadic lifestyle

00:13:15.290 --> 00:13:16.427
as well.

00:13:16.427 --> 00:13:17.510
The philosophy in itself--

00:13:17.510 --> 00:13:19.410
Sikh means student.

00:13:19.410 --> 00:13:23.330
So to see me already being
a student of life, me

00:13:23.330 --> 00:13:26.030
getting an education, being
an elementary school teacher--

00:13:26.030 --> 00:13:28.820
all school schoolteachers
have signed up

00:13:28.820 --> 00:13:30.810
to be lifelong learners as well.

00:13:30.810 --> 00:13:33.160
And I think it's
that natural need

00:13:33.160 --> 00:13:36.450
to try to learn as
much as you can.

00:13:36.450 --> 00:13:39.480
And again, the way my
parents have taught it to me

00:13:39.480 --> 00:13:42.380
was about being students
of God, worshipping God.

00:13:42.380 --> 00:13:45.830
And the thing is, all the
texts are written in poetry.

00:13:45.830 --> 00:13:47.480
So you can easily
take the word God

00:13:47.480 --> 00:13:49.370
and replace it with the truth.

00:13:49.370 --> 00:13:50.870
So you can be
students of the truth.

00:13:50.870 --> 00:13:53.043
And now, instead of
looking at the will of God,

00:13:53.043 --> 00:13:54.710
you can be looking
at the will of truth.

00:13:54.710 --> 00:13:57.860
And that can be everything from
respecting what gravity is,

00:13:57.860 --> 00:14:00.107
respecting human
nature, understanding

00:14:00.107 --> 00:14:02.190
how the world works and
becoming students of that.

00:14:02.190 --> 00:14:07.040
And with that, it's an endless
journey of learning the truth.

00:14:07.040 --> 00:14:09.620
So what my truth is
today on this level

00:14:09.620 --> 00:14:12.290
won't be my truth in five years.

00:14:12.290 --> 00:14:14.330
So now you become
this lifelong learner,

00:14:14.330 --> 00:14:17.330
understanding universal
truths and personal truths

00:14:17.330 --> 00:14:21.170
and trying to have them come
to terms with each other.

00:14:21.170 --> 00:14:23.510
And that's a never
ending journey for me.

00:14:23.510 --> 00:14:25.272
So for me in the
beginning, there

00:14:25.272 --> 00:14:27.230
was a lot of rejection
for it because there are

00:14:27.230 --> 00:14:29.737
a lot of cultural influences.

00:14:29.737 --> 00:14:31.820
So when I first started
rapping, people were like,

00:14:31.820 --> 00:14:33.380
oh, this guy thinks he's black.

00:14:33.380 --> 00:14:34.250
Why is he rapping?

00:14:34.250 --> 00:14:36.470
And I'm sitting there
like, every hymn I was ever

00:14:36.470 --> 00:14:40.490
taught to memorize rhymed.

00:14:40.490 --> 00:14:45.230
Over half of the gurus that
I was taught to learn from

00:14:45.230 --> 00:14:48.620
ran armies and had
bodies under their belt.

00:14:48.620 --> 00:14:53.510
And I was listening to
gangster rap before NWA.

00:14:53.510 --> 00:14:54.930
My gurus rhymed and killed.

00:14:54.930 --> 00:14:57.050
This was something I
was always exposed to.

00:14:57.050 --> 00:14:59.630
If you go to temples
in Toronto, they

00:14:59.630 --> 00:15:04.100
have pictures, photographs
of dead bodies hanging

00:15:04.100 --> 00:15:07.400
on the walls of young men
who fought for a cause

00:15:07.400 --> 00:15:08.510
and gave up their lives.

00:15:08.510 --> 00:15:10.340
We were exposed to this.

00:15:10.340 --> 00:15:12.830
We were a very martial people.

00:15:12.830 --> 00:15:16.640
We've always been encouraged
to be [NON-ENGLISH SPEECH]..

00:15:16.640 --> 00:15:18.830
[NON-ENGLISH SPEECH]
means always be ready,

00:15:18.830 --> 00:15:21.400
always be prepared.

00:15:21.400 --> 00:15:23.580
Some people believe in
a ceremonial dagger.

00:15:23.580 --> 00:15:25.900
But the reality of that is
we've been fighting wars,

00:15:25.900 --> 00:15:27.525
and we've been doing
that because we've

00:15:27.525 --> 00:15:30.160
been a minority our
entire existence.

00:15:30.160 --> 00:15:32.440
So seeing the connections,
and as I got older,

00:15:32.440 --> 00:15:34.232
being able to own it
myself and being like,

00:15:34.232 --> 00:15:36.065
all right, here are the
elements that really

00:15:36.065 --> 00:15:37.480
connect with me authentically.

00:15:37.480 --> 00:15:41.780
And it is to be not only a
student, but to be a soldier,

00:15:41.780 --> 00:15:44.170
and then learning
that hey, the soldier

00:15:44.170 --> 00:15:47.800
isn't that guy who's just
simply outside on a Saturday

00:15:47.800 --> 00:15:50.448
afternoon, protesting
for Palestine.

00:15:50.448 --> 00:15:52.240
The soldier is the one
fighting the biggest

00:15:52.240 --> 00:15:54.340
battles on the inside.

00:15:54.340 --> 00:15:55.900
And those are the
ones that I really

00:15:55.900 --> 00:16:00.070
had to take a lot of times to
deal with, especially when I

00:16:00.070 --> 00:16:01.690
decided I was going to--

00:16:01.690 --> 00:16:04.570
talking about the issues
that were happening

00:16:04.570 --> 00:16:07.060
in Sri Lanka when the
Tamil Tigers were fighting

00:16:07.060 --> 00:16:10.330
for their freedom, or the
ongoing conflict in Israel

00:16:10.330 --> 00:16:14.148
and Palestine, or any human
rights issue that exists,

00:16:14.148 --> 00:16:15.940
you write about them,
and you explore them.

00:16:15.940 --> 00:16:17.500
But then you take it deeper,
and you're like, wait,

00:16:17.500 --> 00:16:19.580
it's not about these
political issues.

00:16:19.580 --> 00:16:23.470
It's about power, oppression,
greed, human nature,

00:16:23.470 --> 00:16:28.150
and then our best source for
all of that is ourselves.

00:16:28.150 --> 00:16:30.730
And then I started talking
about my oppression

00:16:30.730 --> 00:16:35.620
when I oppress, when I'm
chasing power, when I'm greedy.

00:16:35.620 --> 00:16:39.010
And that really
changed the trajectory

00:16:39.010 --> 00:16:41.650
of my art and my work,
and that brought me

00:16:41.650 --> 00:16:43.510
closer back to Sikh
heritage, which

00:16:43.510 --> 00:16:46.180
was always talking about that.

00:16:46.180 --> 00:16:49.510
If you read any of the
writings in the hymns in Sikh

00:16:49.510 --> 00:16:52.600
scriptures, there's no talk
about growing your beard

00:16:52.600 --> 00:16:54.640
or wearing a turban.

00:16:54.640 --> 00:16:57.040
This is a lot more
heritage and cultural.

00:16:57.040 --> 00:17:00.700
This just talks about your
lust, your greed, your anger,

00:17:00.700 --> 00:17:03.700
your attachment, your ego,
how these things impact

00:17:03.700 --> 00:17:04.900
our happiness.

00:17:04.900 --> 00:17:07.130
And there's no talk
about, this is a sin.

00:17:07.130 --> 00:17:08.470
This is right, this is wrong.

00:17:08.470 --> 00:17:10.630
There's just
writings from people

00:17:10.630 --> 00:17:13.060
who are trying
their best to have

00:17:13.060 --> 00:17:16.010
a healthy relationship with
what they consider the truth.

00:17:16.010 --> 00:17:17.950
And you're sharing
it poetically,

00:17:17.950 --> 00:17:21.400
and I think for our people
being in North India,

00:17:21.400 --> 00:17:24.460
North India has been the
front door for invaders

00:17:24.460 --> 00:17:26.640
since Alexander the Great.

00:17:26.640 --> 00:17:29.740
And for any group of
people to have art,

00:17:29.740 --> 00:17:31.630
you need some stability.

00:17:31.630 --> 00:17:33.730
We didn't have the
stability out there.

00:17:33.730 --> 00:17:36.670
So the moment our families
started coming and crossing

00:17:36.670 --> 00:17:40.210
the pond over North America
in the '60s and the '70s,

00:17:40.210 --> 00:17:42.543
we're that generation who had
that stability to explore.

00:17:42.543 --> 00:17:44.502
So that's why you're
seeing an explosion of it.

00:17:44.502 --> 00:17:45.790
That's why you have Rupi Kaur.

00:17:45.790 --> 00:17:46.840
That's why you have Lily Singh.

00:17:46.840 --> 00:17:47.800
That's why you have [INAUDIBLE].

00:17:47.800 --> 00:17:48.910
That's why you have me.

00:17:48.910 --> 00:17:51.070
You're having this
first crop of artists,

00:17:51.070 --> 00:17:53.920
but now, that's the
beginning of the wave.

00:17:53.920 --> 00:17:56.590
Because when people
ask me, who's

00:17:56.590 --> 00:17:59.350
the artistic person in
your family, I don't know.

00:17:59.350 --> 00:18:01.180
I don't know if it's
my mom or my dad.

00:18:01.180 --> 00:18:03.400
They were never
given the opportunity

00:18:03.400 --> 00:18:05.690
to explore creativity.

00:18:05.690 --> 00:18:07.960
My father has a master's
degree, and he didn't have

00:18:07.960 --> 00:18:09.700
an opportunity to explore that.

00:18:09.700 --> 00:18:11.890
He came to Canada
and drove a cab.

00:18:11.890 --> 00:18:17.195
And so for us, it's trying to
pick up where they left off

00:18:17.195 --> 00:18:19.570
because we never had-- and
even in our history as people,

00:18:19.570 --> 00:18:22.155
we don't have a
lineage of poets.

00:18:22.155 --> 00:18:23.280
We have maybe two or three.

00:18:23.280 --> 00:18:27.300
We don't have a lineage
of artists and painters.

00:18:27.300 --> 00:18:30.220
There's a lot of hiccups in our
history because of invasions

00:18:30.220 --> 00:18:32.587
and most recently,
when the British came.

00:18:32.587 --> 00:18:33.920
And they changed a lot of stuff.

00:18:33.920 --> 00:18:36.520
So for me now, it's about
finding myself, but also trying

00:18:36.520 --> 00:18:38.050
to continue this heritage.

00:18:38.050 --> 00:18:41.480
And the challenges are not so
much people on the outside,

00:18:41.480 --> 00:18:42.730
but also people on the inside.

00:18:42.730 --> 00:18:47.020
Because fundamentalism is people
who find comfort in the past.

00:18:47.020 --> 00:18:48.940
And people are
like, hey, this is

00:18:48.940 --> 00:18:52.190
what a guy with a beard and
turban is supposed to do.

00:18:52.190 --> 00:18:53.590
You're not looking like that.

00:18:53.590 --> 00:18:55.690
You're not acting like that.

00:18:55.690 --> 00:18:57.230
You're making us uncomfortable.

00:18:57.230 --> 00:18:59.170
So I get a lot of
resistance internally

00:18:59.170 --> 00:19:00.400
within the community.

00:19:00.400 --> 00:19:03.310
And instead of having a chip
on my shoulder and being like,

00:19:03.310 --> 00:19:05.470
my people and my
culture don't accept me,

00:19:05.470 --> 00:19:09.070
I have to recognize that hey,
they're speaking their fear.

00:19:09.070 --> 00:19:12.040
Because now I'm in a
position of influence.

00:19:12.040 --> 00:19:15.370
And they want me to
adhere to culture

00:19:15.370 --> 00:19:18.670
because they're afraid
that I can rewrite culture.

00:19:18.670 --> 00:19:20.050
And that's the challenge.

00:19:20.050 --> 00:19:23.980
But it's my job to
continue the story

00:19:23.980 --> 00:19:26.950
and write culture and
understand that hey,

00:19:26.950 --> 00:19:29.530
my parents had this many tools.

00:19:29.530 --> 00:19:31.180
I have the education
and the life

00:19:31.180 --> 00:19:33.010
experiences with
this many tools.

00:19:33.010 --> 00:19:35.290
What can I do to ensure
that the next generation has

00:19:35.290 --> 00:19:36.550
this many tools?

00:19:36.550 --> 00:19:40.000
So, it's been an
interesting journey,

00:19:40.000 --> 00:19:43.005
but I think me, and
specifically Lily, just--

00:19:43.005 --> 00:19:44.380
because I stay
with her out here,

00:19:44.380 --> 00:19:46.150
and we spend a lot
of time together--

00:19:46.150 --> 00:19:50.110
we talk about this a lot as
to recognizing our influence.

00:19:50.110 --> 00:19:51.550
People are copying my tattoos.

00:19:51.550 --> 00:19:53.500
People tie their turban
the way I tie it.

00:19:53.500 --> 00:19:56.360
And you're like, OK, well,
there's a responsibility here

00:19:56.360 --> 00:19:56.860
now.

00:19:56.860 --> 00:19:59.950
And then also just with
the newer generation,

00:19:59.950 --> 00:20:01.930
folks don't care.

00:20:01.930 --> 00:20:04.150
They don't label
as much anymore.

00:20:04.150 --> 00:20:07.540
Generation Z, they
don't care what you are.

00:20:07.540 --> 00:20:10.720
And what influence
are we having on them?

00:20:10.720 --> 00:20:12.580
And how can we have
a positive influence?

00:20:12.580 --> 00:20:15.100
So for me, it's like the
overarching theme I'm always

00:20:15.100 --> 00:20:18.580
encouraging and trying to
shove down everybody's throat

00:20:18.580 --> 00:20:21.760
is not look like me, act
like me, dress like me.

00:20:21.760 --> 00:20:25.790
It's chase
self-awareness like me.

00:20:25.790 --> 00:20:27.450
And if you want to
be like me, that

00:20:27.450 --> 00:20:31.480
means being the best version
of you, whatever that is.

00:20:31.480 --> 00:20:35.130
And if that's a purple
mohawk, and a tutu,

00:20:35.130 --> 00:20:38.300
and roller skates
to work, then do it.

00:20:38.300 --> 00:20:40.110
That's what I'm
encouraging everybody

00:20:40.110 --> 00:20:42.300
to kind of do within
their own, and be

00:20:42.300 --> 00:20:43.530
your own student of truth.

